# Fixture: fm9-inverse-negated-property-path
# Finding: Failure Mode 9 — Inverse negated property path precedence
# Spec: SPARQL 1.1 §9.3; grammar PathElt ::= PathPrimary PathMod?,
#       PathPrimary ::= '^' PathElt | ...
# Mailing list: public-sparql-dev "inverse negated property paths" (2012)
#
# Hypothesis: ^!(rdf:type) means "match any triple where ?s is the OBJECT
# and the predicate is NOT rdf:type" — i.e., (^(!(rdf:type))), invert the
# negated set. This is NOT the same as !(^rdf:type) (negate the inverse
# path). The ^ wraps the entire PathElement including the negated property
# set. Operator precedence in property path evaluation is a known divergence.
#
# Divergence: An implementation that parses ^!(p) as !(^p) evaluates an
# entirely different path expression. The combined fixture below exercises
# all three forms in one query to maximise the chance of exposing precedence
# disagreement across parsers.
# Grammar-level behaviour: parses successfully.

SELECT * WHERE {
  ?s <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> ?type .
  ?s !(<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type>|<http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#sameAs>) ?o .
  ?s ^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> ?class .
  ?s ^!(<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type>) ?x .
}
